As to the nature of the motive particles separated from the mass of the blood, it is our opinion that they are of a saline-sulphureous quality. I think, namely, that sulphureous and saline particles brought to the highest volatility iu the mass of the blood by its continuous fermentation in the manner elsewhere described, and most intimately joined together, are separated from the blood by the action of the muscular parenchyma and stored up in the motor
